headline: Virginia Gov. Ralph Northam reportedly asks for time to clear his name after Cabinet meeting
subHeadline: Northam changes story on racist yearbook photo, denies he is in blackface or in KKK robe; reaction and analysis from 'The Five.'

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Hello, everyone. I'm Dana Perino along with Emily Compagno, Juan Williams, Jesse Watters, and Greg Gutfeld. It's 5 o'clock in New York City, and this is "The Five." Virginia Democratic Governor Ralph Northam resisting growing calls to resign over a racist photo that appears under his name in his 1984 medical school yearbook. Northam reportedly meeting with his cabinet today and asking for time to clear his name. The Virginia governor initially apologizing after the photo came out on Friday, but is now saying it's not him.

utterances.speaker: GOV. RALPH NORTHAM, D-VA.
utterances.sentences: My first impression actually that this couldn't be me. But there was so much hurt that I was feeling people were calling, so I reached out and apologized to people for this very picture being on my page.  Last night, I finally had a chance to sit down and look at the photograph in detail. It is definitely not me. I can tell by looking at it.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: These developments coming as a growing number of prominent Democrats say the governor needs to step aside.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: There is no way you can continue to be the governor.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: He needs to resign.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: He should remain in the public square by explaining and talking and working to heal, but he should do it from a position of private citizen. I think he should resign now.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: I think that the governor should resign. I think he's shown himself sort of irreparably damaged in terms of his ability to govern.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED MALE
utterances.sentences: I believe he's a decent person, but I think he has to resign.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: He should resign. And I saw the photo when I -- after I saw you guys last night, so disturbing, so racist.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: All right, Juan, let me ask you about the governor. So he's in this position now. He's asking for time to clear his name, which -- understand that, but the entire party is like falling out from under him.

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: I think it was almost immediate. I can think of one exception that said, you know, we need to give him time. We don't want to leap to conclusions. I think lots of people, including on this panel said, hey, maybe the Democrats have some regret over Al Franken. Remember how quickly people pushed him over. But I think this is a different situation in part because he's the governor. He's in a singular position and he's clearly lost moral authority in part because -- and I don't see this as a pond, but dance or board dancing that he did at that news conference where he comes out and apologizes, then it looks like he's not apologizing, and he says, oh, it wasn't me, but, of course, he apologized and left the clear impression that it was him.  And then the whole thing about black face with the Michael Jackson thing, I mean, that was -- that could have been Saturday Night Live, right? So, it's the idea that he has totally done a bad job of representing himself, but I think on a larger scale, there's so much politics involved here. The people who broke the story, a far-right wing website, clearly was given a tip because of the position that he had taken on pro-choice issues. And then secondly, that Northam himself seems to have a lack of appreciation for exactly how awful this was because he says, oh, this happens in the 1980's. Hey, this is like so many years after the Civil Rights Act, after the civil rights movement. He's acting like, oh, well, you know, something a teenager -- he wasn't a teenager. He was in medical school.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: So, I think, for the party, Dana, to get to your point, the reason that Democrats are jumping on or jumping off the Northam boat, it's in part because there would be such obvious charges of hypocrisy from Republicans who say, hey, you guys hold a high standard for Republicans and the like. You're always criticizing Steve King or Barack -- or Donald Trump, whenever they're charged with something that's potentially racist. How can you allow this to go on in your own midst? So I think you've seen everyone, and I say everyone. I'm talking about former governors of the state of Virginia, to people who are in congress, you know, Schumer, Pelosi, say that he's got to go.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Does it matter though, Greg, where the tip came from? In terms if it's like this tip --

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: The only reason why it matters is where was Gillespie's team -- did they see this but not see this? He -- I agree with Juan. I mean, for me, he's testing the limits of forgive and not forget but to forgive because I believe that people do change over time. I mean, if you look at, obviously, Bird was in the KKK and Barack Obama eulogized him, I believe. So, I mean, people can change. And things that we might be doing now is something I always think about that half a century from now, we may be seen as, like, I can't believe people did that or said that. It just happens that -- sometimes we aren't aware of how time changes.  And I'm with Juan that this is in the '80s, so it's kind of strange. But, OK, I want to forgive him but I don't think I can. And the only reason I think I can is because he has smeared people racially before. He's gone out -- I mean, Gillespie is a case of it. I mean, he didn't, you know --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: We have an example of that. So Gillespie was his opponent. And Gillespie -- he -- and the Gillespie campaign had accepted the Republican Governors Association request to be in charge of opposition research, whether that matters or not, whether he should go after people's yearbooks or not. Setting that aside, there was this ad that ran during the campaign. It was about -- after Gillespie had talked about MS-13, he had gotten a lot of criticism for that. A third party group ran this ad. Northam did not disavow it. Watch this.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, and you had some people defending him today, Emily, saying that -- well, he has done good things for the African-American community in Virginia, and they pointed to -- he pushed through -- he was the final -- finally able to push through the Medicaid expansion in Virginia, for example.

utterances.speaker: EMILY COMPAGNO, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Yeah. I think what you're saying and this to -- you know, humans are complex, of course. You can't have someone be all bad or all good, or with rare exceptions, let's say, so absolutely, in that weighing of the entire situation. But I do feel like a couple things. Number one, to me the irony is that the largest lapse of judgment that I see beside, obviously, those horrible photos, but his management and reaction to this entire thing. Like, to me, the largest demonstration of his inability to serve the people would be this bungling entire situation. And like you said, you know, is this how he reacts? Exactly. Is this the kind of thoughtful, measured response we want from a governor? Or is this someone who clearly --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He looked to his wife when they're asking about moonwalking. He almost was going to moonwalk.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: I know --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Jesse, even though he was like, no, no, no. You don't moonwalk.

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: No, no. You wouldn't -- yeah, if you do it, you moonwalk your way out of that press conference and resign. It's the only way to do it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He has been moonwalking. He's been trying to walk forwards but he keeps going backwards.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That's right. Because, you know, at first he was apologizing and now he's not apologizing because he doesn't recognize himself.   Now, if you look at a photo on your own yearbook page and you say I don't recognize myself in blackface, it's not about being able to see if your features behind the blackface. It's about remembering you putting on blackface, standing next to a guy in a robe and then telling the editor, yes, I'm using this photo in my yearbook. You don't put strangers' pictures in your yearbook page.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: He's trying to save black face.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: The guy is a stone cold liar, and he's also a masochist. Look at these numbers, 41 percent drop in approval among Virginia voters, 50 percent drop among independents, and he still thinks like he's going to hang on.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: You hear from people, Emily, that, like, Virginians are saying they're just sad for the commonwealth. They want to figure out a way to put this behind them. And I don't think that they can put it behind them unless he resigns.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: I agree. And also, I think the interesting about that yearbook, you know, that -- it was like riddled with racist photos actually. There's a whole host of them that were -- I mean, I don't know how you can get much worse from that photo, but you can if you go and look up the other photos. So --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yeah, this makes the Kavanaugh yearbook look like fun and games.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Oh, totally. I mean, that was athletes comparatively. And, yeah, it seems to me that it would be best for his career moving forward if there's an opportunity for redemption. To me, it would come after a resignation and acceptance of responsibility, let alone his comments the week prior --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: You know, if there is any good from this, you know, people say - -

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Get rid of the yearbooks.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: If people say to me, what is it about black face? And I'm like, no, you know, I hear from people now all over say, oh, obviously, that's racist. That was intended to denigrate, to belittle people, make people look lazy, stupid, all the rest. I think that's gone. People understand this is wrong.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I think so. All right, ahead, my Super Bowl queso set offs an Internet meme firestorm, and I'll make The Five taste it. But first, on the eve of the State of the Union, President Trump says Democrats can't beat him in 2020. You'll hear from him next.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: As the race for the White House heats up, President Trump calling out 2020 Democratic hopefuls for their policy proposals. He's also slamming their attempted strategy to try to defeat him.

utterances.speaker: PRESIDENT DONALD TRUMP
utterances.sentences: The only way they can win, because they can't win the election, is to bring out the artificial way of impeachment. What they're doing on abortion, what they're doing on high taxes, what they're doing at the border, what they're doing in so many different ways, they want to cut our military, they want to take our wealth and give it away, they want to tax people, not 70 percent, it's 100 percent. So, if you look at what they're running on, they can't win.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Meanwhile, yesterday marked a year from the Iowa caucuses. A new poll has Joe Biden, the former vice president, leading the field of potential Democratic presidential candidates by double digits among likely Iowa caucus goers. So, Emily, if you were a Democrat, who would you be backing?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: I don't like that hypothetical question. None of the above I think is the best answer.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well done. Don't fall for that trap.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: But I think what's interesting about this, you know, as we were kind of discussing these topics, the impeachment thing, you know, I think that Pelosi understands that that would not be the way to go unless there was something specific that they're running on. I think that would be a really bad move. And for my understanding, after Clinton's impeachment failed, not only -- not only did two-thirds of Americans hate the impeachment process and basically feel like it was a waste of time in their taxpayer dollars. But you know, his job performance approval ratings rose, but his moral character approval declined. And so, apparently that was the largest factor in the election of Bush, subsequently, was his honesty and moral character. So I do think it's kind of a fine line to walk, but certainly it would be a poor move.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Jesse, a lot of talk in D.C. about questions about Trump from fellow Republicans increasing in volume. Last week, we have the Senate Republicans vote. I think it was 40-something Senate Republicans voted against Trump's withdrawal from Syria. You have the whole controversy about the intelligence chiefs. Do you see that as a bigger threat than the Democrats to President Trump at this point?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Absolutely not. I think it's a healthy party and the party allows difference of opinions, unlike the Democratic Party where it's pretty lockstep behind Pelosi. But that's fine. I don't think anybody is going to run against him or primary him. On Biden, he doesn't have the machine, he doesn't have the money, he doesn't have the electricity, he has -- he's just has no base within the party. So that, as Dana said before, all name recognition. He doesn't want to run because I think he knows he's not going to win.   And I think the president is previewing his whole strategy right now. The Democrats are open borders, pro-infanticide, tax and spend, socialists, you know, take away your healthcare, and that's how he's going to run and that's a pretty stark contrast strategy that's going to get a lot of eyeballs.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, if he doesn't want to run, Dana, he won't run, talking about Joe Biden.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Right. And he has time -- because he has all of that name ID, he has time to spend and sit back, decide. Although, this -- it's been going on for a long time, right -- around Thanksgiving, remember they floated the story that said over the holidays he's going to make a decision. And then it was, well, by the end of the month. And now we're well into February and it's still like, oh, I'm really not sure --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Maybe he meant like Valentine's Day?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Those holidays?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I think -- you know, Jesse listed all those things about the Democrats. There's a thing going around on Twitter of all the Democrats had to do was not be crazy. They're like that -- this is just all crazy.  And I thought it was very interesting to watch on this Medicare For All is now a litmus test for the Democrats. They're not running on improving Obamacare. They are running on destroying the private health insurance industry. And you have 80 percent of Americans actually have health insurance through their employer. They're not going to like that. And so, I think it's a very strange way to kick off this campaign, but I'm having fun watching it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: By the way, Greg, so these two don't think that Biden really wants to run. But if he does run, the polls indicate he could beat Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I just don't see how the new Democratic Party is going to choose an older white male. I just think that they're going to come to him, pull him aside and go -- and, you know, I'm going to use Jesse's analogy from last week. I think it was a choose your own adventure? Did you really say that? Democrats at the starting line, they have a choose your own adventure. One, they can go way left and energize the loudest voices, the base, embrace identity politics full on intersectionality or they can choose impeachment which will create the Trump folk hero thing and Pence will become president. And then, if he does get impeached, Trump could actually run as a Democrat and be -- can you imagine those debates with Trump on the Democratic stage beating the crap out of all of them or the third thing could be just pick a winner, like pick a persuasive person --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And go for it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: -- and go for it. You've got two years. And I have a feeling maybe they're scared that they don't have that. But I do think that the Democratic pack is burdened by identity politics and I've talked about it before. But I realize the reason why it's a burden is because it so easy.  Imagine, you don't have to make promises anymore. All I can say is, you know what, I see you as a woman. I see you as a woman and I value your womanhood. That means you don't have to promise jobs, you know, you don't have to promise peace or prosperity. All I have to do is acknowledge your personhood. And I think that's a problem because you're going to have a very thin -- you're going to have very thin gruel --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I asked Emily if she would pick, if she was a Democrat who would she pick. Now, you said just a moment ago, maybe they would have somebody who would be like an x-factor, a surprise --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Right now -- right now, I have to say it's Kamala is in charge.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, really? You think Kamala Harris.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I hate to say -- in the intersectional Olympics, she's like a plus three, right? It's like you have -- it's like -- you know, she's got it. But there could be somebody from the outside who is more of a populist. I mention Cory Booker last Friday as being somebody whose also got, you know --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I thought you were going to have a celebrity or something.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Oh yeah --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I remember --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I say Mark Ruffalo.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Well, remember tomorrow is when Oprah Winfrey --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Oh, Michelle Obama.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: -- Beto O'Rourke here in New York in Times Square.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I think Michelle Obama may still enter.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Jesse might get in it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: All right, will President Trump make a big announcement about the border wall during tomorrow's State of the Union address? That's next right here, so stay with us on The Five.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: President Trump making final preparations for tomorrow night's State of the Union address. This as the president refuses to budge on getting money for the border wall ahead of another possible shutdown.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: Would you shut down the government again?

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.sentences: Well, we're going to have to see what happens on February 15th and --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.sentences: You're not taking it off the table?

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.sentences: Well, I don't take anything off the table. I don't like to take things off the table. It's that alternative. It's national emergency. You need a wall. And anybody that says you don't, they're just playing games.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Nancy Pelosi will be seated directly behind Trump tomorrow night. And that's not stopping the president from blasting the House Speaker over her resistance to the wall.

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.sentences: She knows that you need a barrier. She knows that we need border security. She wanted to win a political point. I happen to think it's very bad politics because basically she wants open borders. She doesn't mind human trafficking, or she wouldn't do this.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: So, Emily, what are your expectations for tomorrow night's State of the Union, and how do you think Nancy Pelosi will behave behind the president?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: I hope that she keeps an, you know, impassive face, obviously, for at least to the decorum of holding that position. My expectations are, you know, it's -- I will say I would not be surprised if in it he called on that emergency declaration if he referenced it. And basically said again, look, this is what I'll do.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: You're predicting state of emergency declaration tomorrow night.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: No. I don't know. I don't want to be held to that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I don't mean to pressure you.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: But I just think -- you know, the more that I looked into it, it's such a viable option, and in large part, just bird's-eye view, because one of the reasons for emergency power is because of the ineptitude and the inability of the government to get it done legislatively or not in a timely fashion. That's exactly what we need right now. So, unless something drastic happens on the other side, which I don't see, because everyone is still playing semantics with wall or barrier or whatever, then what other option do we have?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: All right. Juan, you're going to be down in the swamp tomorrow night.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Well, don't tell Mitch McConnell about your idea because I think the Republicans are pretty clear to President Trump, don't do it. But I don't think he's going to do it tomorrow in any case. I think tomorrow is really, from what the White House is saying, much more about trying to exhibit the capacity to reach out to Democrats and say here are things that we can get done. The five points that they put out so far include things like infrastructure. Like, you know what, hey, both sides, we can work on this. We can get something done, right? And so he wants -- I think, especially in the aftermath of the declining poll numbers that were caused by the shutdown fiasco, say, hey, listen, I am trying to work with these Democrats. They're the ones that aren't doing right and put the pressure on the Democrats. So that's what he'll try to do. The Democrats for their part, they're bringing two illegal immigrants who were working for Trump to sit in the audience to mock him.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Oh, OK. So what -- is Trump's going to call ICE? All right, Dana, the president has usually gotten rave reviews from his State of the Union addresses from the mainstream media. Do the Democrats run any risks, you know, sitting on their hands --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- when he talks about all the great things economically that are happening?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes. So I think there's a high chance that you'll have some heckling or some sort of highly staged walkout by Democrats. I think that President Trump will keep his cool and maybe make a little joke about it and he'll, you know, win hearts and minds back at home. I think that when he is praising troops or certainly talking about the economy and job numbers and unemployment rates, imagine the camera shot then of Senators Harris, Warren, Gillibrand, Booker. There's Congresswoman Tulsi Gabbard. I don't know -- whoever else is running for president. And if they're sitting boot face, you know, looking like they're unhappy, that's not going to be necessarily good for them. But they have a choice to make right now because they have to see if they can stand out from one another. I also think the two big bipartisan pieces tomorrow night will be infrastructure once again around that loop. But Pelosi and Trump has actually talked that they could agree on that. But the other big one is going to be prescription drugs and some sort of a plan to deal with the high cost of prescription drugs. It is not a conservative position, but it is one that you can get bipartisan agreement.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Was last week infrastructure week?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Every week.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Every week is infrastructure. All right, so, Greg, you're not going to be down there.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: No, I'm not. Thank God I'm going to be here minding the store. I'll be at the news deck just, you know, doing my thing. Yeah. This is incredibly tedious, this event. I think they should split it into two and let Maroon 5 play in the intermission. Would that be great? You could serve some of your queso. I finally figured out how we can build a wall. You're queso. Anyway -- you know when that stuff hardens. It ain't --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You know with this thing, though, the so two?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It's time to take stock of the presidency, but it's hard to take stock of this presidency because all the sound and fury of the last two years, it's like impossible to sit back and go, hmm, this cacophony doesn't really match the deeds when you think about the - you subtract the polarizing business model of the media, you have jobs, economy, military, optimism, North Korea, trade, prison reform. All this neat stuff that basically when you take a look at it, the Left should love this guy. He's walking around the planet reducing our military footprint. I mean if you look at North Korea, Tulsi Gabbard should be thanking him. Syria, whether you're against or not, he's just very Left wing. Afghanistan, Yemen, I mean you can disagree with all of this, but the steps being taken, I mean he's moving away from conflicts, shouldn't the Left be embracing this? WATTERS: It's everything the Left said that they were about one and now you're against it just because Donald Trump is for it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: And we're for it because it's Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I noticed ISIS fell off your list.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I know.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Because the intel people said, hey, you know what, they're still there and still trying to kill us.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: You can have two competing thoughts in your head. You know Juan, one of is destroying ISIS. The other one is to continue to destroy ISIS.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: But here is the thing Greg.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Juan doesn't like competition.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I do like competition, but I've got to say that the headline to me was the President did sum up his presidency. He said, he's the best President ever over those last 10 years.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: An understatement, I might add.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That's next two years.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Six months.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Involved in a massive scandal over here, a massive scandal. Dana Perino, she faced a social media mob. We'll tell you all about it, next year. (COMMERCIAL BREAK)

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yes. It was the Super Bowl that wasn't. I don't mean the game which was boring. I mean this. What is this you ask? It's totally OK if you don't know. Most people have never seen something so ghoulish. It's Dana Perino's attempt at queso. I made queso, she wrote like it was a signed confession to a serial killing. I made queso, yes you did. You made queso look like a melted golden retriever.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Oh.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: I think we can agree, this is not something you would put inside you, it's something that would fly out of you after drinking the water at a Tijuana hospital. I don't think I've ever seen anything more inedible in my life and I include prison food. Seriously, no one on death row would touch this. They take the chair first. The picture went viral. Of course, it would. It looks infectious. So, how is this homemade? It looks like the leftovers from the all the oil changes at Jiffy Lube. It looks like a foot spy. You might buy at the chair Noble gift shop. It's the bronzer runoff from the bikini contest. A fondue pot from Three Mile Island. I hear ISIS is taking credit for it. Yes, Dana Perino made queso, it's not her forte. Queso from Perino, it's like Abba doing gangster rap, a care bear doing a lap dance. Of course, Dana took a picture of this bucket of hideous bumbling doom and tweeted it, which is basically making your own kick me sign and taping it to your back. It's going to live forever. utterances.utterance: So, I think, for the party, Dana, to get to your point, the reason that Democrats are jumping on or jumping off the Northam boat, it's in part because there would be such obvious charges of hypocrisy from Republicans who say, hey, you guys hold a high standard for Republicans and the like. So I think you've seen everyone, and I say everyone. I'm talking about former governors of the state of Virginia, to people who are in congress, you know, Schumer, Pelosi, say that he's got to go.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Does it matter though, Greg, where the tip came from? In terms if it's like this tip --

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: The only reason why it matters is where was Gillespie's team -- did they see this but not see this? He -- I agree with Juan. I mean, for me, he's testing the limits of forgive and not forget but to forgive because I believe that people do change over time. I mean, if you look at, obviously, Bird was in the KKK and Barack Obama eulogized him, I believe. So, I mean, people can change. And things that we might be doing now is something I always think about that half a century from now, we may be seen as, like, I can't believe people did that or said that. It just happens that -- sometimes we aren't aware of how time changes. And I'm with Juan that this is in the '80s, so it's kind of strange. But, OK, I want to forgive him but I don't think I can. And the only reason I think I can is because he has smeared people racially before. He's gone out -- I mean, Gillespie is a case of it. I mean, he didn't, you know --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: We have an example of that. So Gillespie was his opponent. And Gillespie -- he -- and the Gillespie campaign had accepted the Republican Governors Association request to be in charge of opposition research, whether that matters or not, whether he should go after people's yearbooks or not. Setting that aside, there was this ad that ran during the campaign. It was about -- after Gillespie had talked about MS-13, he had gotten a lot of criticism for that. A third party group ran this ad. Northam did not disavow it. Watch this.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, and you had some people defending him today, Emily, saying that -- well, he has done good things for the African-American community in Virginia, and they pointed to -- he pushed through -- he was the final -- finally able to push through the Medicaid expansion in Virginia, for example.

utterances.speaker: EMILY COMPAGNO, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Yeah. I think what you're saying and this to -- you know, humans are complex, of course. You can't have someone be all bad or all good, or with rare exceptions, let's say, so absolutely, in that weighing of the entire situation. But I do feel like a couple things. Number one, to me the irony is that the largest lapse of judgment that I see beside, obviously, those horrible photos, but his management and reaction to this entire thing. Like, to me, the largest demonstration of his inability to serve the people would be this bungling entire situation. And like you said, you know, is this how he reacts? Exactly. Is this the kind of thoughtful, measured response we want from a governor? Or is this someone who clearly --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He looked to his wife when they're asking about moonwalking. He almost was going to moonwalk.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: I know --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Jesse, even though he was like, no, no, no. You don't moonwalk.

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: No, no. You wouldn't -- yeah, if you do it, you moonwalk your way out of that press conference and resign. It's the only way to do it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He has been moonwalking. He's been trying to walk forwards but he keeps going backwards.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's right. Because, you know, at first he was apologizing and now he's not apologizing because he doesn't recognize himself. Now, if you look at a photo on your own yearbook page and you say I don't recognize myself in blackface, it's not about being able to see if your features behind the blackface. It's about remembering you putting on blackface, standing next to a guy in a robe and then telling the editor, yes, I'm using this photo in my yearbook. You don't put strangers' pictures in your yearbook page.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He's trying to save black face.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The guy is a stone cold liar, and he's also a masochist. Look at these numbers, 41 percent drop in approval among Virginia voters, 50 percent drop among independents, and he still thinks like he's going to hang on.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: You hear from people, Emily, that, like, Virginians are saying they're just sad for the commonwealth. They want to figure out a way to put this behind them. And I don't think that they can put it behind them unless he resigns.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: I agree. And also, I think the interesting about that yearbook, you know, that -- it was like riddled with racist photos actually. There's a whole host of them that were -- I mean, I don't know how you can get much worse from that photo, but you can if you go and look up the other photos. So --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, this makes the Kavanaugh yearbook look like fun and games.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Oh, totally. I mean, that was athletes comparatively. And, yeah, it seems to me that it would be best for his career moving forward if there's an opportunity for redemption. To me, it would come after a resignation and acceptance of responsibility, let alone his comments the week prior --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: You know, if there is any good from this, you know, people say - -

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Get rid of the yearbooks.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: If people say to me, what is it about black face? And I'm like, no, you know, I hear from people now all over say, oh, obviously, that's racist. That was intended to denigrate, to belittle people, make people look lazy, stupid, all the rest. I think that's gone. People understand this is wrong.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think so. All right, ahead, my Super Bowl queso set offs an Internet meme firestorm, and I'll make The Five taste it. But first, on the eve of the State of the Union, President Trump says Democrats can't beat him in 2020. You'll hear from him next.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: As the race for the White House heats up, President Trump calling out 2020 Democratic hopefuls for their policy proposals. He's also slamming their attempted strategy to try to defeat him.

utterances.speaker: PRESIDENT DONALD TRUMP
utterances.utterance: The only way they can win, because they can't win the election, is to bring out the artificial way of impeachment. What they're doing on abortion, what they're doing on high taxes, what they're doing at the border, what they're doing in so many different ways, they want to cut our military, they want to take our wealth and give it away, they want to tax people, not 70 percent, it's 100 percent. So, if you look at what they're running on, they can't win.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Meanwhile, yesterday marked a year from the Iowa caucuses. A new poll has Joe Biden, the former vice president, leading the field of potential Democratic presidential candidates by double digits among likely Iowa caucus goers. So, Emily, if you were a Democrat, who would you be backing?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: I don't like that hypothetical question. None of the above I think is the best answer.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well done. Don't fall for that trap.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: But I think what's interesting about this, you know, as we were kind of discussing these topics, the impeachment thing, you know, I think that Pelosi understands that that would not be the way to go unless there was something specific that they're running on. I think that would be a really bad move. And for my understanding, after Clinton's impeachment failed, not only -- not only did two-thirds of Americans hate the impeachment process and basically feel like it was a waste of time in their taxpayer dollars. But you know, his job performance approval ratings rose, but his moral character approval declined. And so, apparently that was the largest factor in the election of Bush, subsequently, was his honesty and moral character. So I do think it's kind of a fine line to walk, but certainly it would be a poor move.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Jesse, a lot of talk in D.C. about questions about Trump from fellow Republicans increasing in volume. Last week, we have the Senate Republicans vote. I think it was 40-something Senate Republicans voted against Trump's withdrawal from Syria. You have the whole controversy about the intelligence chiefs. Do you see that as a bigger threat than the Democrats to President Trump at this point?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Absolutely not. I think it's a healthy party and the party allows difference of opinions, unlike the Democratic Party where it's pretty lockstep behind Pelosi. But that's fine. I don't think anybody is going to run against him or primary him. On Biden, he doesn't have the machine, he doesn't have the money, he doesn't have the electricity, he has -- he's just has no base within the party. So that, as Dana said before, all name recognition. He doesn't want to run because I think he knows he's not going to win. And I think the president is previewing his whole strategy right now. The Democrats are open borders, pro-infanticide, tax and spend, socialists, you know, take away your healthcare, and that's how he's going to run and that's a pretty stark contrast strategy that's going to get a lot of eyeballs.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, if he doesn't want to run, Dana, he won't run, talking about Joe Biden.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Right. And he has time -- because he has all of that name ID, he has time to spend and sit back, decide. Although, this -- it's been going on for a long time, right -- around Thanksgiving, remember they floated the story that said over the holidays he's going to make a decision. And then it was, well, by the end of the month. And now we're well into February and it's still like, oh, I'm really not sure --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Maybe he meant like Valentine's Day?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Those holidays?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I think -- you know, Jesse listed all those things about the Democrats. There's a thing going around on Twitter of all the Democrats had to do was not be crazy. They're like that -- this is just all crazy. And I thought it was very interesting to watch on this Medicare For All is now a litmus test for the Democrats. They're not running on improving Obamacare. They are running on destroying the private health insurance industry. And you have 80 percent of Americans actually have health insurance through their employer. They're not going to like that. And so, I think it's a very strange way to kick off this campaign, but I'm having fun watching it.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: By the way, Greg, so these two don't think that Biden really wants to run. But if he does run, the polls indicate he could beat Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I just don't see how the new Democratic Party is going to choose an older white male. I just think that they're going to come to him, pull him aside and go -- and, you know, I'm going to use Jesse's analogy from last week. I think it was a choose your own adventure? Did you really say that? Democrats at the starting line, they have a choose your own adventure. One, they can go way left and energize the loudest voices, the base, embrace identity politics full on intersectionality or they can choose impeachment which will create the Trump folk hero thing and Pence will become president. And then, if he does get impeached, Trump could actually run as a Democrat and be -- can you imagine those debates with Trump on the Democratic stage beating the crap out of all of them or the third thing could be just pick a winner, like pick a persuasive person --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And go for it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- and go for it. You've got two years. And I have a feeling maybe they're scared that they don't have that. But I do think that the Democratic pack is burdened by identity politics and I've talked about it before. But I realize the reason why it's a burden is because it so easy. Imagine, you don't have to make promises anymore. All I can say is, you know what, I see you as a woman. I see you as a woman and I value your womanhood. That means you don't have to promise jobs, you know, you don't have to promise peace or prosperity. All I have to do is acknowledge your personhood. And I think that's a problem because you're going to have a very thin -- you're going to have very thin gruel --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I asked Emily if she would pick, if she was a Democrat who would she pick. Now, you said just a moment ago, maybe they would have somebody who would be like an x-factor, a surprise --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right now -- right now, I have to say it's Kamala is in charge.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, really? You think Kamala Harris.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I hate to say -- in the intersectional Olympics, she's like a plus three, right? It's like you have -- it's like -- you know, she's got it. But there could be somebody from the outside who is more of a populist. I mention Cory Booker last Friday as being somebody whose also got, you know --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I thought you were going to have a celebrity or something.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh yeah --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I remember --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I say Mark Ruffalo.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, remember tomorrow is when Oprah Winfrey --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Oh, Michelle Obama.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: -- Beto O'Rourke here in New York in Times Square.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I think Michelle Obama may still enter.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Jesse might get in it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All right, will President Trump make a big announcement about the border wall during tomorrow's State of the Union address? That's next right here, so stay with us on The Five.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: President Trump making final preparations for tomorrow night's State of the Union address. This as the president refuses to budge on getting money for the border wall ahead of another possible shutdown.

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: Would you shut down the government again?

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.utterance: Well, we're going to have to see what happens on February 15th and --

utterances.speaker: UNIDENTIFIED FEMALE
utterances.utterance: You're not taking it off the table?

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.utterance: Well, I don't take anything off the table. I don't like to take things off the table. It's that alternative. It's national emergency. You need a wall. And anybody that says you don't, they're just playing games.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Nancy Pelosi will be seated directly behind Trump tomorrow night. And that's not stopping the president from blasting the House Speaker over her resistance to the wall.

utterances.speaker: TRUMP
utterances.utterance: She knows that you need a barrier. She knows that we need border security. She wanted to win a political point. I happen to think it's very bad politics because basically she wants open borders. She doesn't mind human trafficking, or she wouldn't do this.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: So, Emily, what are your expectations for tomorrow night's State of the Union, and how do you think Nancy Pelosi will behave behind the president?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: I hope that she keeps an, you know, impassive face, obviously, for at least to the decorum of holding that position. My expectations are, you know, it's -- I will say I would not be surprised if in it he called on that emergency declaration if he referenced it. And basically said again, look, this is what I'll do.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: You're predicting state of emergency declaration tomorrow night.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: No. I don't know. I don't want to be held to that.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I don't mean to pressure you.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: But I just think -- you know, the more that I looked into it, it's such a viable option, and in large part, just bird's-eye view, because one of the reasons for emergency power is because of the ineptitude and the inability of the government to get it done legislatively or not in a timely fashion. That's exactly what we need right now. So, unless something drastic happens on the other side, which I don't see, because everyone is still playing semantics with wall or barrier or whatever, then what other option do we have?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right. Juan, you're going to be down in the swamp tomorrow night.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, don't tell Mitch McConnell about your idea because I think the Republicans are pretty clear to President Trump, don't do it. But I don't think he's going to do it tomorrow in any case. I think tomorrow is really, from what the White House is saying, much more about trying to exhibit the capacity to reach out to Democrats and say here are things that we can get done. The five points that they put out so far include things like infrastructure. Like, you know what, hey, both sides, we can work on this. We can get something done, right? And so he wants -- I think, especially in the aftermath of the declining poll numbers that were caused by the shutdown fiasco, say, hey, listen, I am trying to work with these Democrats. They're the ones that aren't doing right and put the pressure on the Democrats. So that's what he'll try to do. The Democrats for their part, they're bringing two illegal immigrants who were working for Trump to sit in the audience to mock him.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Oh, OK. So what -- is Trump's going to call ICE? All right, Dana, the president has usually gotten rave reviews from his State of the Union addresses from the mainstream media. Do the Democrats run any risks, you know, sitting on their hands --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- when he talks about all the great things economically that are happening?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes. So I think there's a high chance that you'll have some heckling or some sort of highly staged walkout by Democrats. I think that President Trump will keep his cool and maybe make a little joke about it and he'll, you know, win hearts and minds back at home. I think that when he is praising troops or certainly talking about the economy and job numbers and unemployment rates, imagine the camera shot then of Senators Harris, Warren, Gillibrand, Booker. There's Congresswoman Tulsi Gabbard. I don't know -- whoever else is running for president. And if they're sitting boot face, you know, looking like they're unhappy, that's not going to be necessarily good for them. But they have a choice to make right now because they have to see if they can stand out from one another. I also think the two big bipartisan pieces tomorrow night will be infrastructure once again around that loop. But Pelosi and Trump has actually talked that they could agree on that. But the other big one is going to be prescription drugs and some sort of a plan to deal with the high cost of prescription drugs. It is not a conservative position, but it is one that you can get bipartisan agreement.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Was last week infrastructure week?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Every week.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Every week is infrastructure. All right, so, Greg, you're not going to be down there.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: No, I'm not. Thank God I'm going to be here minding the store. I'll be at the news deck just, you know, doing my thing. Yeah. This is incredibly tedious, this event. I think they should split it into two and let Maroon 5 play in the intermission. Would that be great? You could serve some of your queso. I finally figured out how we can build a wall. You're queso. Anyway -- you know when that stuff hardens. It ain't --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You know with this thing, though, the so two?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's time to take stock of the presidency, but it's hard to take stock of this presidency because all the sound and fury of the last two years, it's like impossible to sit back and go, hmm, this cacophony doesn't really match the deeds when you think about the - you subtract the polarizing business model of the media, you have jobs, economy, military, optimism, North Korea, trade, prison reform. All this neat stuff that basically when you take a look at it, the Left should love this guy. He's walking around the planet reducing our military footprint. I mean if you look at North Korea, Tulsi Gabbard should be thanking him. Syria, whether you're against or not, he's just very Left wing. Afghanistan, Yemen, I mean you can disagree with all of this, but the steps being taken, I mean he's moving away from conflicts, shouldn't the Left be embracing this? WATTERS: It's everything the Left said that they were about one and now you're against it just because Donald Trump is for it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: And we're for it because it's Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I noticed ISIS fell off your list.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I know.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Because the intel people said, hey, you know what, they're still there and still trying to kill us.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You can have two competing thoughts in your head. You know Juan, one of is destroying ISIS. The other one is to continue to destroy ISIS.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But here is the thing Greg.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Juan doesn't like competition.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I do like competition, but I've got to say that the headline to me was the President did sum up his presidency. He said, he's the best President ever over those last 10 years.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: An understatement, I might add.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's next two years.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Six months.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Involved in a massive scandal over here, a massive scandal. Dana Perino, she faced a social media mob. We'll tell you all about it, next year. (COMMERCIAL BREAK)

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yes. It was the Super Bowl that wasn't. I don't mean the game which was boring. I mean this. What is this you ask? It's totally OK if you don't know. Most people have never seen something so ghoulish. It's Dana Perino's attempt at queso. I made queso, she wrote like it was a signed confession to a serial killing. I made queso, yes you did. You made queso look like a melted golden retriever.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I think we can agree, this is not something you would put inside you, it's something that would fly out of you after drinking the water at a Tijuana hospital. I don't think I've ever seen anything more inedible in my life and I include prison food. Seriously, no one on death row would touch this. They take the chair first. The picture went viral. Of course, it would. It looks infectious. So, how is this homemade? It looks like the leftovers from the all the oil changes at Jiffy Lube. It looks like a foot spy. You might buy at the chair Noble gift shop. It's the bronzer runoff from the bikini contest. A fondue pot from Three Mile Island. I hear ISIS is taking credit for it. Yes, Dana Perino made queso, it's not her forte. Queso from Perino, it's like Abba doing gangster rap, a care bear doing a lap dance. Of course, Dana took a picture of this bucket of hideous bumbling doom and tweeted it, which is basically making your own kick me sign and taping it to your back. It's going to live forever. You actually made that unholy stew, then forced it on her horrified friends to eat. I could say this is one of those occasions when you're relieved you weren't invited. But you know who's really grateful for Dana's queso? Yes, this guy at Maroon 5's Adam Levine, who is usually the cheesiest thing on earth. Not last night. Dana looked at that tattooed cringe crooning cheese stick of a dork and said, hold my spatula. Adam should buy her dinner for taking the spotlight off his awful performance. Just don't let her cook. You know you deserve it.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It wasn't as - I mean I think it tasted better.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Look at that.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Then it looked--

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Look at the film on that, it's worse than Birth of a Nation.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I tried a new recipe.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I've got it off the Internet.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And they said it would be like Chili's Bar and Grill for - they have great queso there.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: So, I thought I would try it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Chili's was so embarrassed that they had to go on Twitter and deny any culpability.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No, they were very, very--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Is that true?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No. They were nice to me. They said, at least, I was trying to be a good hostess and I attempted to make queso.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Well, you know what--

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: The best thing is I had some leftovers, so I brought it for everybody here.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yes, and we're not having any of it, at least for me.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Jesse is having some.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I'll have some.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: OK. This is when most southwest grill were brought their queso, which of course is amazing. This doesn't feel warm enough.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: What did you make of the game?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: It was the worst. You know I like football, I guess but it was hard to watch. Now some people said to me, oh! if you love defense, it was a great game. But even the defense, you know when I look at the word - I'm looking for--

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: It's not great.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It's pretty good.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Word for Dana.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Is that yours. What's that?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: That's most southwest grill actual queso.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Wait, is your supposed to look white.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: No.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It's chili queso.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Anyway, about the football.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
